{"key":"processedPost-10057559","value":{"id":10057559,"first":10057489,"last":10301946,"when":1238218388,"utime":"03/28/09 08:33 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Typhus said:</b><br />They do it to stop side pinning which can make for slightly better yields as the side pins eat substraight up, it isnt \"needed\" and can be negated by getting solid color containers.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />It's to stop side pinning, but not for that reason, and side pins don't 'eat up' the substrate; mycelium does, and it's everywhere if fully colonized.&nbsp; The idea is that as the mycelium consumes the substrate and it shrinks, the bag pulls in with the substrate, thus there's not the air space around the edges, which is what stimulates side pinning down in that gap.&nbsp; The substrate still shrinks with a solid color tub, thus that doesn't help.<br /><br />Contrary to popular misconception, side pinning isn't caused by light around the edges.&nbsp; Light anywhere on the mycelium will stimulate pinning anywhere else on the mycelium where conditions of fresh air and humidity are conducive to primordia formation.<br />RR","title":"Re: Liner in Sterilite Tub?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}